Virtual Networks

Virtual networking uses software-based controllers or application programming interfaces (APIs) to manage and automate network functions. Its benefits include centralized management, dynamic resource allocation, and simplified network provisioning.

Overlay Network

An overlay network is a virtualized network that uses the physical infrastructure for its operation but functions as an independent network with its own set of services, policies, and virtualized infrastructure nodes. Nodes in the overlay network are connected by virtual links that define a path through physical links in an underlying network. The underlying physical network must be considered when designing or managing the overlay network.

The following figure shows a network with physical nodes that are connected with physical links.

The underlying networks for data centers should typically provide the following:

  • High-capacity resilient fabric

  • Intelligent packet processing

  • Programmability and manageability

The following two figures show two examples of overlay networks that are built on top of an underlay network.

The overlay network provides new capabilities and features:

  • Mobility: This capability tracks endpoints that are attached at the edges.

  • Scale: This capability reduces the core state by distributing and partitioning the state to the network edge.

  • Flexibility and programmability: These capabilities reduce the number of touch points.

Tunneling protocols such as Virtual Extensible LAN (VXLAN), Network Virtualization Using Generic Routing Encapsulation (NVGRE), and Generic Network Virtualization Encapsulation (GENEVE) enable virtual networks to be layered over a physical network infrastructure.

The following tools and platforms support virtualized networks:

  • Cisco Application Centric Infrastructure (ACI) is a software-defined networking solution. It is designed for data centers and automates network provisioning and management for complex workloads.

  • VMware NSX provides network virtualization and security services. It allows the creation of virtual networks within data centers and cloud environments.

  • Microsoft Azure Virtual Network enables the creation of isolated virtual networks in the Azure cloud and supports secure communication between Azure and on-premises infrastructure.

  • Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) allows the creation of isolated networks within Amazon Web Services (AWS). It controls IP addresses, subnets, and routing.

  • Google Cloud VPC provides scalable and flexible networking capabilities for deploying and managing applications on Google Cloud.
